<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<configuration>
  <!--
    ========================================================================================
    CONFIGURATION SECTIONS
    ========================================================================================

    This critical section defines custom configuration sections that extend the standard
    .NET configuration schema. Each section specifies a handler that processes the
    corresponding configuration elements in this file. Without these declarations,
    the application would not recognize custom configuration sections.

    - applicationSettings: Defines strongly-typed application settings for components
      like data access layers. This allows settings to be accessed via Properties.Settings
      with compile-time type checking and IntelliSense support.

    - dataConfiguration: Configures the Microsoft Enterprise Library Data Access Application
      Block. This block provides a consistent API for database operations across different
      database providers, abstracting connection management and command execution.

    - hibernate-configuration: Sets up NHibernate ORM configuration for database mapping,
      sessions, and SQL dialect settings. NHibernate is an object-relational mapping tool
      that maps .NET objects to database tables and handles SQL generation.

    - configBuilders: Enables external configuration builders that can inject sensitive
      data or transform configuration values. This is crucial for secure credential
      management without hardcoding secrets in source control.

    These section declarations must appear before any elements they define, and they
    enable the .NET configuration system to properly parse and validate the custom
    configuration elements used throughout this file.
  -->
  <configSections>
    <sectionGroup name="applicationSettings" type="System.Configuration.ApplicationSettingsGroup, System, Version=4.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=b77a5c561934e089">
      <section name="ALOD.Data.Properties.Settings" type="System.Configuration.ClientSettingsSection, System, Version=4.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=b77a5c561934e089" requirePermission="false" />
    </sectionGroup>
    <section name="dataConfiguration" type="Microsoft.Practices.EnterpriseLibrary.Data.Configuration.DatabaseSettings, Microsoft.Practices.EnterpriseLibrary.Data, Version=4.1.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=31bf3856ad364e35" />
    <section name="hibernate-configuration" type="NHibernate.Cfg.ConfigurationSectionHandler, NHibernate" />
    <section name="configBuilders" type="System.Configuration.ConfigurationBuildersSection, System.Configuration, Version=4.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=b03f5f7f11d50a3a" restartOnExternalChanges="false" requirePermission="false" />
  </configSections>
  <!--
    ========================================================================================
    CONFIGURATION BUILDERS
    ========================================================================================

    This section configures external sources for providing configuration values, greatly
    enhancing security and flexibility in configuration management. Configuration builders
    allow sensitive data to be injected from external sources without storing them in the
    configuration file itself, which is crucial for maintaining security in production
    environments.

    - Secrets: Utilizes User Secrets (a development-time secret manager) to inject sensitive
      data like passwords, API keys, or connection strings without hardcoding them in the
      configuration file. The userSecretsId references a unique identifier for the secret
      store, typically generated per-user or per-environment.

      This approach follows security best practices by:
      * Keeping sensitive information out of source control
      * Allowing different secrets per developer/environment
      * Providing a secure way to manage credentials during development
      * Enabling easy rotation of secrets without code changes

      The User Secrets configuration builder reads from a local secrets.json file (typically
      located at %APPDATA%\Microsoft\UserSecrets\<userSecretsId>\secrets.json) and injects
      values into the configuration at runtime.
  -->
  <configBuilders>
    <builders>
      <add name="Secrets" userSecretsId="39febcb4-89b9-48a5-911a-3c404a9734c1" type="Microsoft.Configuration.ConfigurationBuilders.UserSecretsConfigBuilder, Microsoft.Configuration.ConfigurationBuilders.UserSecrets, Version=3.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=31bf3856ad364e35" />
    </builders>
  </configBuilders>
  <!--
    ========================================================================================
    DATA CONFIGURATION
    ========================================================================================

    This section specifies the default database connection for the Microsoft Enterprise
    Library Data Access Application Block. This block provides a consistent, abstracted
    API for database operations across different database providers, eliminating the need
    to write provider-specific code.

    The defaultDatabase attribute points to the named connection string (e.g., "LOD")
    that will be used by default for all data access operations when no specific
    connection is specified. This allows the application to:

    - Use a single point of configuration for database connections
    - Switch between different databases/environments easily
    - Abstract database provider differences (SQL Server, Oracle, etc.)
    - Implement connection pooling and other optimizations automatically

    The Enterprise Library Data Access Application Block handles:
    - Connection management and pooling
    - Parameterized query execution
    - Transaction management
    - Database provider abstraction
    - Error handling and logging

    This configuration is essential for the application's data access layer to function
    properly with the configured database connections.
  -->
  <dataConfiguration defaultDatabase="LOD" />
  <!--
    ========================================================================================
    CONNECTION STRINGS
    ========================================================================================

    This section defines database connection strings used throughout the application for
    data access operations. Each connection string includes critical information about
    how to connect to a specific database, including server location, database name,
    and authentication method.

    Connection strings are referenced by:
    - NHibernate ORM for object-relational mapping
    - Enterprise Library Data Access Application Block
    - ADO.NET data access code
    - Session state management (for SQL Server session storage)

    Security Considerations:
    - Never store passwords in plain text in production
    - Use integrated security when possible
    - Consider encrypting connection strings in web.config
    - Use different credentials for different environments

    Current Connections:
    - LOD: Primary database for Line of Duty investigations, containing case data,
      user information, and investigation records. Uses integrated Windows authentication
      for development environments.

    - SRXLite: Secondary database for SRX-related functionality, including document
      management and external system integrations. Also uses integrated authentication.

    These connections are critical for the application to function, as all data
    operations depend on them. Connection string changes require careful testing
    to ensure database compatibility and security.
  -->
  <connectionStrings>
    <remove name="LocalSqlServer" />
    <add name="LOD" connectionString="Server=localhost;Database=ALOD;Integrated Security=True;" providerName="System.Data.SqlClient"/>
    <add name="SRXLite" connectionString="Server=localhost;Database=SRXLite;Integrated Security=True;" providerName="System.Data.SqlClient"/>
  </connectionStrings>
  <!--
    ========================================================================================
    APPLICATION SETTINGS
    ========================================================================================

    This section contains key-value pairs that define application-specific configuration
    settings controlling various aspects of the application's behavior. These settings
    are accessed programmatically using ConfigurationManager.AppSettings["key"] and
    provide a flexible way to configure application behavior without code changes.

    The settings are logically grouped below for better organization and maintainability.
    Each group serves a specific functional area of the application:

    AUTHENTICATION & SECURITY SETTINGS:
    Controls user authentication, session management, and security features that protect
    the application and its data.

    - authCookieName: Specifies the name of the authentication cookie used for forms
      authentication. This encrypted cookie contains user session information and is
      critical for maintaining user login state across requests.

    - SingleSession: Enables/disables enforcement of single session per user. When enabled,
      logging in from a new location automatically logs out previous sessions, enhancing
      security for sensitive military applications.

    - CacEnabled: Controls whether Common Access Card (CAC) authentication is enabled.
      CAC cards provide two-factor authentication for Department of Defense personnel.

    - DevLoginEnabled: Allows developer login bypass in development environments,
      facilitating easier testing and debugging without full authentication setup.

    - DeployMode: Indicates the current deployment environment (DEV, TEST, PROD),
      allowing conditional behavior based on environment.

    - AccessDeniedUrl: Specifies the URL to redirect users when they attempt to access
      unauthorized resources, providing a consistent user experience.

    DOCUMENT SERVICE SETTINGS:
    Configuration for the SRX Document Service integration, which handles document
    storage, retrieval, and management for the application.

    - DocServiceUsername/Password: Credentials used to authenticate with the SRX
      Document Service SOAP API for secure document operations.

    - DocServiceStylesheet: CSS file URL used for rendering documents in the SRX system,
      ensuring consistent styling across stored documents.

    - UseDBSign/DbSignDatabase/DbSignUrl: Settings for digital signature functionality,
      allowing electronic signatures on documents when enabled.

    DATABASE & PERFORMANCE SETTINGS:
    Controls database query behavior and file upload limitations to ensure optimal
    performance and prevent resource exhaustion.

    - QueryTimeLimit: Maximum time (in seconds) allowed for database queries to execute.
      This prevents long-running queries from hanging the application and provides
      predictable response times.

    - timeoutDialog/timeoutPrompt: UI timeout settings that control when session
      timeout warnings appear to users, improving user experience.

    - InitialFileSizeUploadLimit: Maximum file size (in bytes) allowed for initial
      file uploads, preventing abuse and managing server resources.

    EMAIL & COMMUNICATION SETTINGS:
    Configuration for email functionality and automated notifications used throughout
    the application for user communications and system alerts.

    - EmailFrom: Default sender email address used for all system-generated emails,
      ensuring consistent branding and deliverability.

    - EmailEnabled: Master switch to enable/disable all email sending functionality,
      useful for testing or maintenance periods.

    - ReminderEmailIsEnabled: Controls whether automated reminder emails are sent
      to users for pending tasks or deadlines.

    UI & DISPLAY SETTINGS:
    Controls user interface appearance, behavior, and external resource links.

    - WaterMark: Text displayed as watermark on generated documents and forms,
      typically indicating classification level (e.g., "For Official Use Only").

    - hostname: Base URL for the application, used for generating absolute links
      and redirects in emails and external communications.

    - ChartImageHandler: Configuration for the ASP.NET Chart control's image storage
      and caching behavior, optimizing chart rendering performance.

    LOGGING & DEBUGGING SETTINGS:
    Controls application logging behavior and debugging features for troubleshooting
    and monitoring application health.

    - DeveloperDebugMode: Enables additional debugging information and verbose logging
      for development and troubleshooting purposes.

    - GenerationTimeLogFile: File path for logging page generation times, useful for
      performance monitoring and optimization.

    - CreateLogFile: Enables/disables creation of log files, allowing control over
      logging overhead in different environments.

    - LogsDirectory: Directory path where application logs are stored, ensuring
      proper log file organization and access.

    TRAINING & EXTERNAL LINKS:
    External links and training resources referenced within the application for
    user education and compliance.

    - HipaaTraining: Link to HIPAA training resources, required for users handling
      sensitive health information in compliance with federal regulations.

    - KeepAliveURL/KeepAliveURL2: URLs used for session keep-alive functionality,
      preventing automatic logout during prolonged user activity.

    These settings provide comprehensive control over application behavior and can
    be modified per environment using web.config transformations.
  -->
  <appSettings>
    <!--
      Authentication & Security Settings:
      Controls user authentication, session management, and security features.
      - authCookieName: Name of the authentication cookie (LODAUTH) used for forms authentication.
      - SingleSession: Enables/disables single session enforcement per user.
      - CacEnabled: Controls CAC (Common Access Card) authentication for military users.
      - DevLoginEnabled: Allows developer login bypass in development environments.
      - DeployMode: Indicates deployment environment (DEV, TEST, PROD).
      - AccessDeniedUrl: Redirect URL when access is denied.
    -->
    <add key="authCookieName" value="LODAUTH"/>
    <add key="SingleSession" value="N"/>
    <add key="CacEnabled" value="N"/>
    <add key="DevLoginEnabled" value="Y"/>
    <add key="DeployMode" value="DEV"/>
    <add key="AccessDeniedUrl" value="~/Public/devlogin.aspx"/>

    <!--
      Document Service Settings:
      Configuration for the SRX Document Service integration, used for document storage and retrieval.
      - DocServiceUsername/Password: Credentials for authenticating with the SRX service.
      - DocServiceStylesheet: CSS file for document rendering.
      - UseDBSign/DbSignDatabase/DbSignUrl: Settings for digital signature functionality.
    -->
    <add key="DocServiceUsername" value="AFLOD"/>
    <add key="DocServicePassword" value="DDRSalod121511*("/>
    <add key="DocServiceStylesheet" value="~/Public/upload.css"/>
    <add key="UseDBSign" value="N"/>
    <add key="DbSignDatabase" value="ALOD_DB"/>
    <add key="DbSignUrl" value="http://localhost:8090/dbsign/server"/>

    <!--
      Database & Performance Settings:
      Controls database query timeouts and file upload limits.
      - QueryTimeLimit: Maximum time (seconds) for database queries to prevent hanging.
      - timeoutDialog/timeoutPrompt: UI timeout settings for user prompts.
      - InitialFileSizeUploadLimit: Maximum file size for uploads (in bytes).
    -->
    <add key="QueryTimeLimit" value="10"/>
    <add key="timeoutDialog" value="5"/>
    <add key="timeoutPrompt" value="25"/>
    <add key="InitialFileSizeUploadLimit" value="5242880"/>

    <!--
      Email & Communication Settings:
      Configuration for email functionality and notifications.
      - EmailFrom: Default sender address for system emails.
      - EmailEnabled: Enables/disables email sending.
      - ReminderEmailIsEnabled: Controls automated reminder emails.
    -->
    <add key="EmailFrom" value="alerts@stanfieldsystems.com"/>
    <add key="EmailEnabled" value="Y"/>
    <add key="ReminderEmailIsEnabled" value="Y" />

    <!--
      UI & Display Settings:
      Controls user interface appearance and behavior.
      - WaterMark: Text displayed as watermark on documents/forms.
      - hostname: Base URL for the application.
      - ChartImageHandler: Configuration for chart image generation and storage.
    -->
    <add key="WaterMark" value="For Official Use Only"/>
    <add key="hostname" value="https://localhost:8090/" />
    <add key="ChartImageHandler" value="storage=file;timeout=20;Url=~/chartImages;" />

    <!--
      Logging & Debugging Settings:
      Controls application logging and debugging features.
      - DeveloperDebugMode: Enables detailed debugging information.
      - GenerationTimeLogFile: Path for logging page generation times.
      - CreateLogFile: Enables/disables log file creation.
    -->
    <add key="DeveloperDebugMode" value="false"/>
    <add key="GenerationTimeLogFile" value="/Logs/generation_timeLog.txt"/>
    <add key="CreateLogFile" value="true"/>
    <add key="LogsDirectory" value="/Alod/Logs"/>

    <!--
      Training & External Links:
      External links and training resources referenced in the application.
      - HipaaTraining: Link to HIPAA training for compliance.
      - KeepAliveURL/KeepAliveURL2: URLs for session keep-alive functionality.
    -->
    <add key="HipaaTraining" value="https://mhslearn.csd.disa.mil"/>
    <add key="KeepAliveURL" value="http://localhost:8090/alod/default.aspx"/>
    <add key="KeepAliveURL2" value="http://localhost:8090/alod/default.aspx/"/>
  </appSettings>
  <!--
    ========================================================================================
    SYSTEM.NET
    ========================================================================================

    This section configures network-related settings for the application, including
    SMTP configuration for email sending functionality. The mailSettings subsection
    configures the SMTP server used by System.Net.Mail classes for sending emails
    from the application.

    Email functionality is used for:
    - User notifications and alerts
    - Automated reminders and deadlines
    - System status communications
    - Password reset and account management emails

    The smtp/network configuration specifies:
    - host: The SMTP server hostname or IP address
    - port: The SMTP server port (typically 25 for SMTP, 587 for SMTP with TLS)

    Security considerations for email configuration:
    - Use authenticated SMTP when possible
    - Enable TLS/SSL encryption for secure email transmission
    - Consider using dedicated email services (SendGrid, AWS SES) for production
    - Validate email addresses and prevent email injection attacks
    - Monitor email sending limits and bounce rates

    In development environments, this often points to a local SMTP server or
    development email service. In production, it should use a reliable SMTP
    provider with proper authentication and encryption.

    The System.Net.Mail classes used by this configuration provide:
    - SMTP client functionality
    - MIME message formatting
    - Attachment support
    - HTML and plain text email formats
    - Error handling and delivery status
  -->
  <system.net>
    <mailSettings>
      <smtp>
        <network host="localhost" port="25"/>
      </smtp>
    </mailSettings>
  </system.net>
  <!--
    ========================================================================================
    APPLICATION SETTINGS (STRONGLY-TYPED)
    ========================================================================================

    This section contains strongly-typed application settings for specific components,
    providing type-safe access to configuration values with compile-time checking and
    IntelliSense support. These settings are generated from Settings.settings files
    in Visual Studio and are accessed via Properties.Settings.Default in code.

    Unlike the appSettings section which uses string keys, these settings provide:
    - Type safety (int, bool, string with validation)
    - Compile-time error checking
    - IntelliSense and auto-completion
    - Default value specification
    - Scoped access (per-assembly/component)

    The settings are organized by component:
    - ALOD.Data.Properties.Settings: Contains settings specific to the data access layer,
      including service endpoints and connection configurations.

      - ALOD_Data_SRXExchange_DocumentService: The URL endpoint for the SRX Exchange
        Document Service SOAP web service. This service handles document storage,
        retrieval, and management operations for the application.

        This setting is critical for:
        * Document upload and download functionality
        * File storage and retrieval operations
        * Integration with external document management systems
        * Maintaining document metadata and versions

    Strongly-typed settings improve code maintainability by:
    - Preventing typos in setting names
    - Providing automatic type conversion
    - Enabling refactoring tools to update references
    - Reducing runtime errors from invalid configurations

    These settings are typically modified through the Visual Studio settings designer
    or directly in the .settings files, which then generate the corresponding
    configuration entries.
  -->
  <applicationSettings>
    <ALOD.Data.Properties.Settings>
      <setting name="ALOD_Data_SRXExchange_DocumentService" serializeAs="String">
        <value>http://localhost:8091/services/documentservice.asmx</value>
      </setting>
    </ALOD.Data.Properties.Settings>
  </applicationSettings>
  <!--
    ========================================================================================
    NHIBERNATE CONFIGURATION
    ========================================================================================

    This section configures NHibernate, the Object-Relational Mapping (ORM) framework
    used throughout the application for database operations. NHibernate maps .NET
    objects to database tables, handles SQL generation, manages database sessions,
    and provides transaction support.

    NHibernate acts as the data access layer, providing:
    - Automatic SQL generation from .NET objects
    - Database abstraction across different providers
    - Connection pooling and session management
    - Transaction management and rollback
    - Caching and performance optimization
    - Lazy loading and eager fetching strategies

    Key configuration elements:
    - session-factory: The main configuration container defining how NHibernate
      connects to and interacts with the database.

      - dialect: Specifies the SQL dialect for the target database (MsSql2005Dialect
        for SQL Server 2005 and later versions). This ensures NHibernate generates
        SQL compatible with the specific database version.

      - connection.provider: The connection provider class that manages database
        connections. DriverConnectionProvider creates connections on demand.

      - connection.driver_class: The database driver class (SqlClientDriver for
        SQL Server) that handles low-level database communication.

      - connection.connection_string_name: References the named connection string
        from the connectionStrings section (typically "LOD").

      - connection.isolation: Sets the transaction isolation level (ReadCommitted)
        to balance consistency and performance.

      - default_schema: Specifies the database schema prefix for all table names
        (ALOD.dbo), allowing multiple applications to share a database.

      - show_sql: When enabled, logs all generated SQL statements to the console/debug
        output, useful for debugging and performance analysis.

      - mapping assembly: Specifies the assembly containing NHibernate mapping files
        (.hbm.xml files) that define how .NET classes map to database tables.

    NHibernate mappings are defined in XML files in the ALOD.Core assembly, following
    the pattern of one .hbm.xml file per entity class. These mappings define:
    - Table and column names
    - Primary keys and relationships
    - Data types and constraints
    - Lazy loading behavior

    This configuration is essential for the application's data persistence and
    retrieval operations, enabling object-oriented database access patterns.
  -->
  <hibernate-configuration xmlns="urn:nhibernate-configuration-2.2">
    <session-factory>
      <property name="dialect">NHibernate.Dialect.MsSql2005Dialect</property>
      <property name="connection.provider">NHibernate.Connection.DriverConnectionProvider</property>
      <property name="connection.driver_class">NHibernate.Driver.SqlClientDriver</property>
      <property name="connection.connection_string_name">LOD</property>
      <property name="connection.isolation">ReadCommitted</property>
      <property name="default_schema">ALOD.dbo</property>
      <property name="show_sql">true</property>
      <!-- HBM Mapping Files -->
      <mapping assembly="ALOD.Core" />
    </session-factory>
  </hibernate-configuration>
  <!--
    ========================================================================================
    SYSTEM.WEB
    ========================================================================================

    This comprehensive section configures ASP.NET runtime settings that control the
    behavior of web applications, including compilation, authentication, session
    management, custom controls, and HTTP modules. This section configures the core
    ASP.NET pipeline and is essential for WebForms-based applications.

    Key configuration areas:

    IDENTITY & IMPERSONATION:
    - identity impersonate="true": Enables Windows identity impersonation for database
      connections. This allows the application to connect to SQL Server using the
      authenticated user's Windows credentials rather than a service account,
      providing better security and audit trails.

    TRACING & DEBUGGING:
    - trace enabled="true" pageOutput="false" requestLimit="100" localOnly="false":
      Configures ASP.NET request tracing for debugging and monitoring. When enabled,
      ASP.NET collects detailed information about each request including execution
      time, query strings, and server variables. The trace.axd handler provides
      access to this information for troubleshooting performance issues and errors.

    COMPILATION SETTINGS:
    - compilation debug="true" batch="false" strict="false" explicit="true"
      targetFramework="4.8.1": Controls how ASP.NET compiles pages and code-behind files.
      Debug mode includes debug symbols for better error information but reduces
      performance. The targetFramework specifies .NET Framework 4.8.1 compatibility.

    PAGE DIRECTIVES & CONTROLS:
    - pages: Configures default settings for all ASP.NET pages, including namespaces,
      control declarations, and theme settings. The theme "DefaultBlue" provides
      consistent styling across the application.

    AUTHENTICATION & SECURITY:
    - authentication mode="Forms": Enables forms-based authentication with cookie
      management. Users log in through a web form, and their identity is maintained
      via an encrypted authentication cookie.

    - customErrors mode="Off": Disables custom error pages to show detailed error
      information, crucial for debugging in development environments.

    SESSION MANAGEMENT:
    - sessionState: Configures ASP.NET session state storage using SQL Server for
      scalability and persistence across web farm deployments. Sessions store user-
      specific data like login information and application state.

    SITE NAVIGATION:
    - siteMap: Defines the site navigation provider that generates menus and breadcrumbs
      based on the Web.sitemap file, providing consistent navigation structure.

    WEB SERVICES:
    - webServices: Enables SOAP protocol support for legacy web service calls,
      allowing the application to consume or provide SOAP-based web services.

    HTTP HANDLERS & MODULES:
    - httpHandlers/httpModules: Register custom handlers and modules that intercept
      and process HTTP requests. These include custom authentication modules,
      NHibernate session management, and charset enforcement.

    These settings form the foundation of the ASP.NET WebForms application architecture,
    controlling everything from user authentication to request processing and response
    generation. They ensure proper integration with IIS and provide the framework
    for the application's web-based functionality.
  -->
  <system.web>
    <identity impersonate="true" />
    <trace enabled="true" pageOutput="false" requestLimit="100" localOnly="false"/>
    <compilation debug="true" batch="false" strict="false" explicit="true" targetFramework="4.8.1">
      <assemblies>
      </assemblies>
      <buildProviders>
        <add extension=".rdlc" type="Microsoft.Reporting.RdlBuildProvider, Microsoft.ReportViewer.Common, Version=10.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=B03F5F7F11D50A3A" />
        <remove extension=".lic" />
        <add extension=".lic" type="System.Web.Compilation.ForceCopyBuildProvider" />
      </buildProviders>
    </compilation>
    <pages controlRenderingCompatibilityVersion="3.5" clientIDMode="AutoID" enableSessionState="true" theme="DefaultBlue">
      <namespaces>
        <clear />
        <add namespace="System" />
        <add namespace="System.Collections" />
        <add namespace="System.Collections.Generic" />
        <add namespace="System.Collections.Specialized" />
        <add namespace="System.Configuration" />
        <add namespace="System.Text" />
        <add namespace="System.Text.RegularExpressions" />
        <add namespace="System.Linq" />
        <add namespace="System.Xml.Linq" />
        <add namespace="System.Web" />
        <add namespace="System.Web.Caching" />
        <add namespace="System.Web.SessionState" />
        <add namespace="System.Web.Security" />
        <add namespace="System.Web.Profile" />
        <add namespace="System.Web.UI" />
        <add namespace="System.Web.UI.WebControls" />
        <add namespace="System.Web.UI.WebControls.WebParts" />
        <add namespace="System.Web.UI.HtmlControls" />
      </namespaces>
      <controls>
        <add tagPrefix="ajax" namespace="AjaxControlToolkit" assembly="AjaxControlToolkit" />
        <add namespace="ALOD.Core.Domain.Common.CustomServerControls" assembly="ALOD.Core" tagPrefix="ALod" />
        <add tagPrefix="lod" tagName="ModuleHeader" src="~/Secure/Shared/UserControls/ModuleHeader.ascx" />
        <add tagPrefix="lod" tagName="TabNavigator" src="~/Secure/Shared/UserControls/TabNavigator.ascx" />
        <add tagPrefix="lod" tagName="TabControls" src="~/Secure/Shared/UserControls/TabControls.ascx" />
        <add tagPrefix="lod" tagName="SearchControl" src="~/Secure/Shared/UserControls/SearcherControl.ascx" />
        <add tagPrefix="lod" tagName="unitSearcher" src="~/Secure/Shared/UserControls/unitSearcher.ascx" />
        <add tagPrefix="ajaxToolkit" assembly="AjaxControlToolkit" namespace="AjaxControlToolkit" />
      </controls>
    </pages>
    <authentication mode="Forms">
      <forms name="formsauth" timeout="299" loginUrl="default.aspx" defaultUrl="~/Secure/Welcome.aspx" />
    </authentication>
    <customErrors mode="Off" />
    <authorization>
      <!-- Allow everybody else -->
      <allow users="*" />
    </authorization>
    <sessionState allowCustomSqlDatabase="true" cookieless="UseDeviceProfile" mode="SQLServer" sqlConnectionString="LOD" timeout="31" />
    <siteMap enabled="true" defaultProvider="LodSiteMap">
      <providers>
        <add name="LodSiteMap" type="ALODWebUtility.Providers.LodSiteMapProvider" siteMapFile="~/Web.sitemap" securityTrimmingEnabled="true" />
        <remove name="MySqlSiteMapProvider" />
      </providers>
    </siteMap>
    <webServices>
      <protocols>
        <add name="HttpGet" />
        <add name="HttpPost" />
      </protocols>
    </webServices>
    <httpHandlers>
      <add path="Reserved.ReportViewerWebControl.axd" verb="*" type="Microsoft.Reporting.WebForms.HttpHandler, Microsoft.ReportViewer.WebForms, Version=10.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=b03f5f7f11d50a3a" validate="false" />
      <add path="ScriptResource.axd" verb="GET,HEAD" type="System.Web.Handlers.ScriptResourceHandler, System.Web.Extensions, Version=4.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=31bf3856ad364e35" validate="false" />
      <add path="WebResource.axd" verb="GET" type="System.Web.Handlers.AssemblyResourceLoader, System.Web, Version=4.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=b03f5f7f11d50a3a" validate="false" />
    </httpHandlers>
    <httpModules>
      <add name="CharsetEnforcement" type="ALODWebUtility.Common.CharsetEnforcementModule, ALODWebUtility" />
      <add name="NHibernateSessionModule" type="ALOD.Data.NHibernateSessionModule, ALOD.Data" />
      <add name="Session" type="System.Web.SessionState.SessionStateModule" />
    </httpModules>
  </system.web>
  <!--
    ========================================================================================
    SYSTEM.WEBSERVER
    ========================================================================================

    This section contains IIS-specific settings for integrated pipeline mode, including
    modules, handlers, security headers, and static content configuration. These settings
    apply when running on IIS 7+ in integrated mode and ensure proper integration with
    the web server.

    VALIDATION:
    - validation validateIntegratedModeConfiguration="false": Disables strict validation
      of configuration for integrated mode, allowing legacy configurations to work
      properly with IIS integrated pipeline.

    HTTP MODULES:
    - modules: Registers HTTP modules that intercept and process requests in the IIS
      integrated pipeline. These modules handle authentication, session management,
      NHibernate session lifecycle, and other cross-cutting concerns.

    HTTP HANDLERS:
    - handlers: Maps file extensions and URL patterns to specific handlers that process
      requests. This includes handlers for reports, scripts, images, and web resources.

    DEFAULT DOCUMENT:
    - defaultDocument: Specifies the default files to serve when a directory is requested
      without a specific file name. This ensures proper default page behavior.

    SECURITY HEADERS:
    - httpProtocol/customHeaders: Adds security headers to HTTP responses to protect
      against common web vulnerabilities like clickjacking and content sniffing.

    STATIC CONTENT:
    - staticContent: Configures MIME types and caching behavior for static files like
      CSS, JavaScript, and images. Proper MIME type configuration ensures browsers
      handle files correctly, while caching settings optimize performance.

    ERROR HANDLING:
    - httpErrors existingResponse="PassThrough": Configures how IIS handles HTTP errors,
      allowing detailed error information to pass through for debugging.

    These settings are crucial for:
    - Proper IIS integration and request processing
    - Security hardening with HTTP headers
    - Performance optimization through caching
    - Correct handling of different file types
    - Debugging and error diagnosis

    The integrated pipeline mode allows ASP.NET modules and handlers to participate
    in all requests, not just those mapped to ASP.NET, providing comprehensive
    request processing capabilities.
