    ========================================================================================
    SYSTEM.SERVICEMODEL
    ========================================================================================

    This section configures Windows Communication Foundation (WCF) services, which enable
    secure, reliable, and transacted messaging between applications. WCF provides a
    unified programming model for building service-oriented applications that can
    communicate across process, machine, and network boundaries.

    WCF services support multiple communication protocols:
    - HTTP/HTTPS for web-based communication
    - TCP for high-performance binary communication
    - Named Pipes for same-machine communication
    - MSMQ for queued messaging
    - Custom transports and protocols

    The configuration sections include:

    BINDINGS:
    - bindings: Defines communication protocols and transport settings for services.
      This includes security settings, encoding formats, and reliability options.
      Common binding types include wsHttpBinding, netTcpBinding, and basicHttpBinding.

    CLIENT ENDPOINTS:
    - client: Defines client-side endpoints for consuming external WCF services.
      Each endpoint specifies the service address, binding, and contract.

    Currently, this section is empty (bindings and client are empty), indicating that
    no active WCF services are configured in this application. However, the section
    is present for future expansion if WCF services need to be added.

    WCF services would be used for:
    - Inter-application communication
    - Exposing business logic as web services
    - Integrating with external systems
    - Building distributed applications

    When WCF services are added, this section would contain:
    - Service endpoint definitions
    - Binding configurations with security and performance settings
    - Behavior configurations for error handling and metadata exposure
    - Client endpoint configurations for service consumption

    The presence of this section ensures that WCF configuration is available if
    needed, and it provides a placeholder for future service-oriented architecture
    requirements.
  -->
  <system.serviceModel>
    <bindings />
    <client />
  </system.serviceModel>
  <!--
    ========================================================================================
    LOCATION-SPECIFIC OVERRIDES
    ========================================================================================

    This section provides custom configuration settings that apply only to specific
    paths or pages in the application, allowing fine-grained control over settings
    for particular functionality. Location overrides take precedence over global
    settings for the specified paths, enabling targeted configuration changes.

    The location element allows different configuration sections to be applied to
    specific URLs or virtual paths within the application. This is useful for:

    - Disabling security features for specific pages (like rich text editors)
    - Increasing resource limits for file upload pages
    - Applying different authentication rules to certain areas
    - Customizing error handling for specific functionality

    CURRENT OVERRIDES:

    RICH TEXT EDITOR PAGES:
    - EditMemo.aspx, MemoTemplates.aspx, WelcomePageBanner.aspx: These pages use
      rich text editors that require request validation to be disabled. Request
      validation normally prevents potentially dangerous content (like HTML/script)
      from being submitted, but rich text editors legitimately need to submit HTML.

      The override sets requestValidationMode="2.0" to disable ASP.NET request
      validation for these specific pages, allowing rich content editing while
      maintaining security for the rest of the application.

    FILE UPLOAD LIMITS:
    - Global override (empty path): Increases the maximum request length to 1GB
      (1048576 KB) for file uploads across the entire application. This allows
      large document uploads required for military line-of-duty investigations,
      which may include extensive documentation and evidence files.

      The httpRuntime maxRequestLength setting controls the maximum size of HTTP
      requests, including file uploads. The default is 4MB, which is insufficient
      for document-heavy applications.

    SECURITY CONSIDERATIONS:
    - Location overrides should be used sparingly and with careful consideration
    - Disabled request validation increases XSS vulnerability risk
    - Large file upload limits can be abused for DoS attacks
    - Always validate and sanitize input even when validation is disabled

    IMPLEMENTATION NOTES:
    - Location elements are processed in order, with more specific paths taking
      precedence over general ones
    - Settings in location blocks override global settings for that path only
    - Child configuration elements inherit from parent locations unless explicitly
      overridden

    These overrides provide the flexibility needed for specialized functionality
    while maintaining security and performance for the general application.
  -->
  <!-- Disable request validation for rich text editors -->
  <location path="Secure/Shared/Memos/EditMemo.aspx">
    <system.web>
      <httpRuntime requestValidationMode="2.0" />
    </system.web>
  </location>
  <location path="Secure/Shared/Admin/MemoTemplates.aspx">
    <system.web>
      <httpRuntime requestValidationMode="2.0" />
    </system.web>
  </location>
  <location path="Secure/Shared/Admin/WelcomePageBanner.aspx">
    <system.web>
      <httpRuntime requestValidationMode="2.0" />
    </system.web>
  </location>

  <!-- Increase max request length for file uploads -->
  <location>
    <system.web>
      <httpRuntime maxRequestLength="1048576" />
    </system.web>
  </location>
</configuration>